# Vertical Slice Implementation

Build thin end-to-end slices that work, then thicken. Avoid completing entire horizontal layers (all backend → all frontend → all tests) before validating anything.

## Plan in Slices, Not Layers

When planning a feature, decompose by **user-observable behavior**, not by architectural layer.

- BAD: `1. Migrations. 2. Models. 3. Controllers. 4. Routes. 5. Blade views. 6. JS. 7. Manual test.`
- GOOD: `1. Slice A: simplest happy path end-to-end (DB → controller → view, hardcoded if needed). 2. Slice B: add validation + error path. 3. Slice C: edge case X.`

Each slice should be **independently testable in the browser / via tinker** before moving on.

## Tracer Bullet First

First slice = thinnest possible path that touches every layer the feature needs:

- Stub data is fine (hardcoded array, fake response).
- One field instead of ten.
- One role/permission case instead of all.
- No styling polish.

Goal: prove the wiring works. Find integration issues in minute 5, not hour 5.

## Test As You Go

After each slice:

- Run it manually (browser, tinker, artisan command).
- Check logs / network tab.
- Confirm DB state if relevant.

Do NOT batch all testing to the end. Bugs found one slice at a time are cheap; bugs found after 6 layers stacked are expensive to localize.

## When To Use Horizontal

Horizontal-first is acceptable only when:

- Pure refactor with no behavior change (and tests already exist).
- Trivial CRUD scaffold from a generator.
- Migration-only or config-only change.

Otherwise: default to vertical slices.

## Communicating The Plan

When presenting a plan, structure it as:

```
Slice 1 (tracer): <user action> → <visible result>. Stubs: <list>.
Slice 2: <what gets real / what edge case added>.
Slice 3: ...
```

Not as a layer checklist.
